<taxonomicName authority="Huo &amp; Du" authorityName="Huo &amp; Du" authorityYear="2022" box="[298,648,1857,1881]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Perlodinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="384" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tibetensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[298,529,1857,1881]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="384">Perlodinella tibetensis</emphasis>
Huo &amp; Du
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[657,739,1857,1881]" pageId="6" pageNumber="384">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[657,739,1857,1881]" pageId="6" pageNumber="384" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, male habitus. A: the smaller individual, dorsal and ventral; B: the larger individual with distinct tergal spots, dorsal and ventral.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810255" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6810255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810255/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" startId="7.[151,250,774,798]" targetBox="[157,1420,184,746]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,774,834]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,289,774,798]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">FIGURE 13.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Huo &amp; Du" authorityName="Huo &amp; Du" authorityYear="2022" box="[297,645,774,798]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Perlodinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tibetensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[297,528,774,798]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Perlodinella tibetensis</emphasis>
Huo &amp; Du
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[653,735,774,798]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[653,735,774,798]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, male. A–B: head and pronotum (newly emerged/body sclerotized); C: forewing; D: hindwing.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="385" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,880,2023]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,880,906]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Male</emphasis>
: Micropterous, forewing length 
<quantity box="[620,714,880,907]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4 mm</quantity>
, hindwing length 
<quantity box="[912,1006,880,907]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3 mm</quantity>
, body length 
<quantity box="[1155,1274,880,907]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" unit="mm" value="12.0" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="11.0">11–13 mm</quantity>
(n = 6). Abdomen slightly sclerotized, bearing long yellowish hairs. Terga 8–9 without sensilla patches or sclerotized dots (
<figureCitation captionStart-0="FIGURE 14" captionStart-1="FIGURE 15" captionStart-2="FIGURE 16" captionStartId-0="8.[151,250,1980,2004]" captionStartId-1="9.[151,250,1642,1666]" captionStartId-2="10.[151,250,846,870]" captionTargetBox-0="[159,1428,529,1952]" captionTargetBox-1="[159,1428,186,1612]" captionTargetBox-2="[159,1428,185,818]" captionTargetId-0="figure-140@8.[154,1433,525,1957]" captionTargetId-1="figure-30@9.[154,1434,181,1618]" captionTargetId-2="figure-20@10.[154,1433,181,822]" captionTargetPageId-0="8" captionTargetPageId-1="9" captionTargetPageId-2="10" captionText-0="FIGURE 14. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., male terminalia. A: dorsal view; B: ventral view; C: apex of epiproct, dorsal view; D: apex of epiproct, lateral view; E: everted epiproct, lateral view." captionText-1="FIGURE 15. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., male terminalia. A: dorsal view; B: lateral view; C: ventral view; D: caudal view; E–F: tergal sensilla patches, dorsal view (newly emerged/body sclerotized); G: penis, partially everted, dorsal view (A, B, C, G are from the same male)." captionText-2="FIGURE 16. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., male terminalia after treating by 10% KOH. A: dorsal view; B: lateral view; C: tergum 10 and paraprocts, dorsal view; D: paraprocts, caudal view." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810257" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810259" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810261" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6810257/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6810259/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/6810261/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Figs. 14–16</figureCitation>
). Tergum 10 yellowish and smooth medially; posterior margin heavily sclerotized, curved upward; sensilla basiconica arranged in a V-shape on the posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[798,935,988,1015]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1642,1666]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,186,1612]" captionTargetId="figure-30@9.[154,1434,181,1618]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 15. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., male terminalia. A: dorsal view; B: lateral view; C: ventral view; D: caudal view; E–F: tergal sensilla patches, dorsal view (newly emerged/body sclerotized); G: penis, partially everted, dorsal view (A, B, C, G are from the same male)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810259" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810259/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Figs. 15E–F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[946,997,988,1014]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="10.[151,250,846,870]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,185,818]" captionTargetId="figure-20@10.[154,1433,181,822]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 16. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., male terminalia after treating by 10% KOH. A: dorsal view; B: lateral view; C: tergum 10 and paraprocts, dorsal view; D: paraprocts, caudal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810261" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810261/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">16C</figureCitation>
). Paraproct divided into a subtriangular apical membrane with a typical sclerotized band, and a basic sclerite; apical half of the sclerite slender, hooklike, and curved outward, sharp on apex (
<figureCitation box="[573,690,1060,1087]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1642,1666]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,186,1612]" captionTargetId="figure-30@9.[154,1434,181,1618]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 15. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., male terminalia. A: dorsal view; B: lateral view; C: ventral view; D: caudal view; E–F: tergal sensilla patches, dorsal view (newly emerged/body sclerotized); G: penis, partially everted, dorsal view (A, B, C, G are from the same male)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810259" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810259/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Figs. 15D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[703,789,1060,1086]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="10.[151,250,846,870]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,185,818]" captionTargetId="figure-20@10.[154,1433,181,822]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 16. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., male terminalia after treating by 10% KOH. A: dorsal view; B: lateral view; C: tergum 10 and paraprocts, dorsal view; D: paraprocts, caudal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810261" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810261/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">16C–D</figureCitation>
). The membranous epiproct bears sparse spines, divided into three isometric spherical lobes. The paired basal lobe swollen; apical lobe blunt apically (
<figureCitation box="[1220,1356,1096,1122]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1980,2004]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,529,1952]" captionTargetId="figure-140@8.[154,1433,525,1957]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 14. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., male terminalia. A: dorsal view; B: ventral view; C: apex of epiproct, dorsal view; D: apex of epiproct, lateral view; E: everted epiproct, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810257" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810257/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Fig. 14C–E</figureCitation>
). Penis (partially everted) membranous, dorsal base bearing small asperities (
<figureCitation box="[930,1034,1132,1159]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1642,1666]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,186,1612]" captionTargetId="figure-30@9.[154,1434,181,1618]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 15. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., male terminalia. A: dorsal view; B: lateral view; C: ventral view; D: caudal view; E–F: tergal sensilla patches, dorsal view (newly emerged/body sclerotized); G: penis, partially everted, dorsal view (A, B, C, G are from the same male)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810259" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810259/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Fig. 15G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,880,2023]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,296,1168,1194]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Female:</emphasis>
Coloration similar to males (
<figureCitation box="[638,724,1168,1194]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1684,1708]" captionTargetBox="[174,1416,939,1654]" captionTargetId="figure-61@10.[167,1421,931,1661]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 17. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., female habitus.A: macropterous; B: the sole brachypterous individual from Meiduo, Coqen County." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810263" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810263/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
). Macropterous, forewing length 
<quantity box="[1110,1236,1168,1195]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" unit="mm" value="14.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="14.0">14–15 mm</quantity>
, hindwing length 
<quantity box="[151,274,1204,1231]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" unit="mm" value="12.5" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="12.0">12–13 mm</quantity>
, body length 
<quantity box="[425,545,1204,1231]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" unit="mm" value="14.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="13.0">13–15 mm</quantity>
(n = 12) or brachypterous, forewing length 
<quantity box="[1035,1102,1204,1231]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" unit="mm" value="9.0">9 mm</quantity>
, hindwing length 
<quantity box="[1302,1369,1205,1231]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
, body length 
<quantity box="[230,311,1240,1267]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" unit="mm" value="14.0">14 mm</quantity>
(n = 1). Yellow spots between the hind ocelli and median occiput, at least two patterns present on females (see 
<figureCitation box="[297,380,1276,1302]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1957,1981]" captionTargetBox="[156,1432,1507,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-55@11.[156,1432,1505,1933]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 19. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., female, head and pronotum. A–B: yellow spot inverted triangular; C–D: yellow spot oval." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810269" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810269/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
). Wings pale yellowish to smoky gray, translucent; veins dark brown (
<figureCitation box="[1168,1305,1276,1302]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 17" captionStart-1="FIGURE 18" captionStartId-0="10.[151,250,1684,1708]" captionStartId-1="11.[151,250,1457,1481]" captionTargetBox-0="[174,1416,939,1654]" captionTargetBox-1="[182,1400,193,1422]" captionTargetId-0="figure-61@10.[167,1421,931,1661]" captionTargetId-1="figure-30@11.[172,1414,181,1433]" captionTargetPageId-0="10" captionTargetPageId-1="11" captionText-0="FIGURE 17. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., female habitus.A: macropterous; B: the sole brachypterous individual from Meiduo, Coqen County." captionText-1="FIGURE 18. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., wings of macropterous female. A: forewing; B: hindwing." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810263" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810267" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6810263/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6810267/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Figs. 17–18</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,880,2023]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">
Abdomen dark brown; sterna yellowish laterally, with a pair of lateral dark spots; subgenital plate short and sclerotized, variable; median posterior margin heavily sclerotized and bilobate. There are four morphs of female subgential plates (
<figureCitation box="[352,501,1384,1410]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="12.[151,250,636,660]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,184,610]" captionTargetId="figure-20@12.[151,1436,181,613]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 20. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., female terminalia (corresponding to the same four females in Fig. 19). A–D: variation of subgenital plates, morphs 1–4; the outlines are marked in red." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810271/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Figs. 20A–D</figureCitation>
), with the posterior margin with a small median extension (
<figureCitation box="[1156,1260,1384,1410]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="12.[151,250,636,660]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,184,610]" captionTargetId="figure-20@12.[151,1436,181,613]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 20. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., female terminalia (corresponding to the same four females in Fig. 19). A–D: variation of subgenital plates, morphs 1–4; the outlines are marked in red." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810271/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Fig. 20A</figureCitation>
), posterior margin truncated (
<figureCitation box="[314,416,1420,1446]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="12.[151,250,636,660]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,184,610]" captionTargetId="figure-20@12.[151,1436,181,613]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 20. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., female terminalia (corresponding to the same four females in Fig. 19). A–D: variation of subgenital plates, morphs 1–4; the outlines are marked in red." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810271/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Fig. 20B</figureCitation>
), posterior margin with small lateral processes (
<figureCitation box="[954,1057,1420,1446]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="12.[151,250,636,660]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,184,610]" captionTargetId="figure-20@12.[151,1436,181,613]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 20. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., female terminalia (corresponding to the same four females in Fig. 19). A–D: variation of subgenital plates, morphs 1–4; the outlines are marked in red." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810271/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Fig. 20C</figureCitation>
), and posterior margin M-shaped, the lateral process on each side longer and narrowed (
<figureCitation box="[753,858,1456,1482]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="12.[151,250,636,660]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,184,610]" captionTargetId="figure-20@12.[151,1436,181,613]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 20. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., female terminalia (corresponding to the same four females in Fig. 19). A–D: variation of subgenital plates, morphs 1–4; the outlines are marked in red." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810271/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Fig. 20D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,880,2023]" box="[199,422,1492,1518]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,297,1492,1518]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Nymph:</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,880,2023]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,255,1528,1554]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Egg:</emphasis>
General color brown. Slender, trilateral, with three longitudinal ridges (
<figureCitation box="[1070,1155,1528,1554]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1455,1479]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,721,1432]" captionTargetId="figure-61@12.[154,1433,721,1432]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 21. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., egg. A: lateral view; B: top view; C: bottom view; D: sketch." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810273" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810273/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
). Collar is a short brown ring, cylindrical with a broad base. Anchor mushroom-shaped with massive stem, evenly covered with more small globular bodies. Each side of the egg with 4–6 short transverse rows of micropyles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,880,2023]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">
Under the observation by optical scopes, the egg of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huo &amp; Du" authorityYear="2022" box="[789,923,1636,1662]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Perlodinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tibetensis">
<emphasis box="[789,923,1636,1662]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">P. tibetensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has no obvious visible difference in shape or structure from 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Klapalek" authorityYear="1912" box="[316,421,1672,1698]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Perlodinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kozlovi">
<emphasis box="[316,421,1672,1698]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">P. kozlovi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[436,576,1672,1698]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1455,1479]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,721,1432]" captionTargetId="figure-61@12.[154,1433,721,1432]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 21. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., egg. A: lateral view; B: top view; C: bottom view; D: sketch." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810273" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810273/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Fig. 21 A–D</figureCitation>
) except the small globular bodies near the basic anchor are darker than others (
<figureCitation box="[159,269,1708,1734]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1455,1479]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,721,1432]" captionTargetId="figure-61@12.[154,1433,721,1432]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 21. Perlodinella tibetensis Huo &amp; Du sp. nov., egg. A: lateral view; B: top view; C: bottom view; D: sketch." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810273" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810273/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Fig. 21 A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="385" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,880,2023]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,1744,1770]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Etymology:</emphasis>
The scientific name is a Latin adjective derived from the name of 
<collectingRegion box="[1082,1140,1744,1770]" country="China" name="Xizang" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Tibet</collectingRegion>
where it is the most widespread 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Klapalek" authorityYear="1912" box="[231,371,1780,1806]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Perlodinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[231,371,1780,1806]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Perlodinella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known in this area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="385" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,880,2023]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,324,1816,1842]" pageId="7" pageNumber="385">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The new species can be distinguished by the completely black pronotum, the absence of sensilla basiconica on male tergum 9, V-shaped arrangement of sensilla basiconica on male tergum 10, and the outwardcurving male paraprocts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
